ST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["see   Cocker  .","habitational name from a group of villages in Somerset named with Coker, from a Celtic river name meaning ‘crooked’.","English (southeastern):"],"variants":[{"name":"Coaker","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Coker  ."]},{"name":"Cocker","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): nickname for a quarrelsome person, from Middle English <i>coker</i> ‘fighter, wrangler’.","English: occupational name, ‘one who puts up hay in cocks’, a seasonal occupation.","Probably an Americanized form of German   Kocher  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Coker was born about 1425, in Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert William Coker, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth Turges, was 26. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Avice Mallett. He died in 1514, in Dorset, England, at the age of 90."},"et":{"Abt 1425–1514":"umbes 1425–1514","1425–1514":"1425–1514","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1455–1529":"1455–1529","1480–Fema